Metabolite Set Enrichment Analysis (MSEA) for metabolomics community

Atsushi Fukushima1* and Kozo Nishida2**

1RIKEN Center for Sustainable Resource Science
2RIKEN Quantitative Biology Center

*afukushima@gmail.com
**knishida@riken.jp

Abstract

Instructions for the MSEAp package.

Package: MSEAp

1 Introduction

One of the ultimate goals in systems biology is to elucidate the genotype-phenotype relationship in cellular systems [1]. Integrated ‘omics’ approaches have received particular attention. Most omics analyses monitor the levels of target molecules like transcripts and metabolites. In this context, enrichment analysis approaches can be combined with pathway analysis to evaluate whether a particular molecular group is significantly over-represented, for example Gene Set Enrichment Analysis (GSEA) [2-3]. In meteabolomics, one of promising approaches is Metabolite Set Enrichment Analysis (MSEA) [4]. MSEAp is an R package for performing MSEA using both plant and animal metabolic pathways and metabolite-sets. The package can import pre-defined pathways like KEGG and SMPDB and user-defined metabolite sets in gmt format. Their metabolite sets are integrated and used for MSEA calculation. Given a metabolite-set or pathway annotation of metabolites, significance of the over-representation of the metabolites within the pathways is determined by a Fisher’s exact test. The visualization is based on previously established, a web server MSEA in MetaboAnalyst [5]. The package also contains pre-defined and extracted AraCyc that are publicly available and our curated metabolite-sets from MeKO [6], Arabidopsis flavonoid pathways (Tokimatsu, Nishida et al., in preparation), and literatures in plant metabolomics (AtMetExpress, in preparation).

3 Getting started

library(MSEAp)
data(mset_SMPDB_format_KEGG)
data(kusano)
res <- msea(mset_SMPDB_format_KEGG, kusano)
plot(res)

4 Appetizer

4.1 Importing user’s defined metabolite-sets

You can import user’s defined metabolite-sets using read.gmt() function:

file <- system.file("extdata", "sample_SMPDB.gmt", package = "MSEAp")
smp <- read.gmt(file)

4.2 Importing KGML file

The function kgml.import() can extract compound set from KGML file (*.xml) to list.

## file <- system.file("extdata/map00260.xml", package="KEGGgraph")## KGML downloaded from KEGG ftp
## kgml.import(file)

4.3 Importing KEGG pathways

The function setup.KEGG.gmt.R() generates metabolite-sets using the KEGG REST API.

res <- setup.KEGG.gmt(listformat = TRUE)
res[[1]]

4.4 Conversion of KEGG’s tar.gz into metabolite-set

The function setupPathwayClass() performs convertion of KEGG’s tar.gz files (e.g. hsa.tar.gz) to metabolite-set list.

## filepath <- "./hsa.tar.gz" ## *.tar.gz downloaded from KEGG
## res <- setupPathwayClass(filepath) ## convert to list

4.5 Metabolite-sets

You can see more datasets:

help(package = "MSEAp")

4.6 For plant scientists

You can perform MSEA using AraCyc pathways and our curated metabolite sets (flavonoid pathways and some litterature).

data(mset_AraCyc_format_KEGG)
data(mset_AtMetExpress_Stress_format_KEGG)
data(mset_AtMetExpress_Flavonoids_format_KNApSAcK)
mset <- c(
  mset_AraCyc_format_KEGG,
  mset_AtMetExpress_Stress_format_KEGG,
  mset_AtMetExpress_Flavonoids_format_KNApSAcK
  )
length(mset) ## 281 metabolite-sets
## [1] 281
data(fukushima17_INC)
head(fukushima17_INC)

5 Visalization of MSEA results

To help interpreting MSEA result, we also implemented barplot and dotplot for visualization.

data(mset_SMPDB_Metabolic_format_HMDB)
data(msea.example)
res <- msea(mset_SMPDB_Metabolic_format_HMDB, msea.example)

dotplot(res)  ## You may have to zoom this plot in RStudio and other R working environments

barplot(res)  ## You can see the same plot by plot()
